    <h1>Design Process at Devex</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Reading time 4 minutes</p>
  </section>
  
  <section>
    <h2>Project Overview</h2>
    <p>Over the past three years at Devex, we have undergone a <strong>big transformation</strong> in the way we approach the <strong>design work</strong>.</p>
    <p>As the most senior designer, I have <strong>led many of these changes</strong> with the goal of improving communication and establishing an integrated process.</p>
  </section>
  
  <section>
    <h2>A look back to the starting point</h2>
    <p>When I joined Devex, I found myself as the most senior designer, taking on the responsibility of leading design decisions with little context. The main challenges were:</p> 
    <ul>
      <li>The Design team shifted from being involved in the product development to focusing purely on the design process, modifying the dynamics between designers and the rest of the team.</li>  
      <li>Business stakeholders were concerned about the velocity of the Product Team.</li>    
      <li>While there was some documentation on previous UX work, there was no defined design process.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>On top of that there was business as usual and all the projects that required design work so they didn't become a bottleneck for the rest of the team.</p>
  </section>
  
  <section>
    <h2>Redefining design scope and process</h2>
    <p>Since the designers were no longer in charge of implementing the UI, the way the work was shared between designers and developers, mostly with frontend engineers, needed to be redefined.</p>
    <p>Even though most of the components behaviour was already clear due to the internal UI Toolkit, I realised that the regular refinement meetings often got derailed discussing the high level details of the proposed designs. This resulted in other tasks not being refined.</p>
    <p>To solve this, I proposed and started leading <strong><em>Design Critique</em> sessions</strong> to create a specific space for gathering feedback and share the rationale behind the designs created, without interrupting other established ceremonies.</p>
