  <section>
    <h2>Increasing the velocity</h2>
    <p>Product team velocity was a concern and project scopes were usually quite big mostly due to technical restrictions. To address this issue, I started <strong>breaking projects into <em>Iterations</em></strong>, explaining them during the <em>Design Critiques</em> and structuring the sessions around their feasibility.</p>
    <p>Working like this improved the speed but in some cases the agreed iterations still implied a lot of work and the resulting work process felt too waterfall-like. We needed to find a more practical way.</p>
    <p>I began listing all the proposed <strong>changes as <em>actionable items</em></strong>. This allowed us to share them with business stakeholders, define <strong>priorities based on <em>impact vs. effort assessments</em></strong> and structure iterations in a much leaner way.</p>  
    <p>At this point, all the information was available in a single Figma file. With a lot of help and support from one of our POs, we started <strong>gathering feedback earlier and asynchronously</strong>. Resulting in a time-efficient and effective way of communicating.</p>
